# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anycast-routing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] The first documented use of anycast routing for topological load-balancing of Internet-connected services was in 1989; the technique was first formally documented in the IETF four years later.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] It was first applied to critical infrastructure in 2001 with the anycasting of the I-root nameserver.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Early objections to the deployment of anycast routing centered on the perceived conflict between long-lived TCP connections and the volatility of the Internet's routed topology.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] In practice, such problems were not observed, and these objections dissipated by the early 2000s.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Many initial anycast deployments consisted of DNS servers, using principally UDP transport.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Measurements of long-term anycast flows revealed very few failures due to mid-connection instance switches, far fewer (less than 0.017% or "less than one flow per ten thousand per hour of duration" according to various sources) than were attributed to other causes of failure.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Numerous mechanisms were developed to efficiently share state between anycast instances.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] And some TCP-based protocols, notably HTTP, incorporated "redirect" mechanisms, whereby anycast service addresses could be used to locate the nearest instance of a service, whereupon a user would be redirected to that specific instance prior to the initiation of any long-lived stateful transaction.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Anycast is implemented in the Internet via Border Gateway Protocol (BGP), where multiple hosts (usually in different geographic areas) are given the same anycast IP address and they all announce it to their BGP table.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Routers consider these to be alternative routes to the same destination, even though they are actually routes to different destinations with the same address.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Routers will often select the path with fewer hops, which leads to the one closer to the client as being selected (often faster).
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] It doesn't always happen, as some routers will choose other metrics (least congested, cheapest).
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Anycast is supported explicitly in the IPv6 addressing architecture.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] The lowest address within an IPv6 subnet (interface identifier 0) is reserved as the "Subnet Router" anycast address.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] In addition, the highest 128 interface identifiers within a subnet are also reserved as anycast addresses.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] The method used in IPv4 of advertising multiple routes in BGP to multiply-assigned unicast addresses also still works in IPv6, and can be used to route packets to the nearest of several geographically dispersed hosts with the same address.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] This approach, which does not depend on anycast-aware routers, has the same use cases together with the same problems and limitations as in IPv4.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] With the growth of the Internet, network services increasingly have high-availability requirements.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] As a result, operation of anycast services has grown in popularity among network operators.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] All Internet root nameservers are implemented as clusters of hosts using anycast addressing.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] All 13 root servers A–M exist in multiple locations, with 11 on multiple continents.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] (Root servers B and H exist in two U.S. locations.) The servers use anycast address announcements to provide a decentralized service.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] This has accelerated the deployment of physical (rather than logical) root servers outside the United States.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Many commercial DNS providers have switched to an IP anycast environment to increase query performance and redundancy, and to implement load balancing.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] In IPv4 to IPv6 transitioning, anycast addressing may be deployed to provide IPv6 compatibility to IPv4 hosts.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] This method, 6to4, uses a default gateway with the IP address *192.88.99.1*.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] This allows multiple providers to implement 6to4 gateways without hosts having to know each individual provider's gateway addresses.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] 6to4 has been deprecated in response to native IPv6 becoming more prevalent.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Content delivery networks may use anycast for actual HTTP connections to their distribution centers, or for DNS.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Because most HTTP connections to such networks request static content such as images and style sheets, they are generally short-lived and stateless across subsequent TCP sessions.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] The general stability of routes and statelessness of connections makes anycast suitable for this application, even though it uses TCP.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Anycast rendezvous point can be used in Multicast Source Discovery Protocol (MSDP) and its advantageous application as Anycast RP is an intra-domain feature that provides redundancy and load-sharing capabilities.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] If the multiple anycast rendezvous point is used, IP routing automatically will select the topologically closest rendezvous point for each source and receiver.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] It would provide a multicast network with the fault tolerance requirements.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Anycast allows any operator whose routing information is accepted by an intermediate router to hijack any packets intended for the anycast address.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] While this at first sight appears insecure, it is no different from the routing of ordinary IP packets, and no more or less secure.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] As with conventional IP routing, careful filtering of who is and is not allowed to propagate route announcements is crucial to prevent man-in-the-middle or blackhole attacks.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] The former can also be prevented by encrypting and authenticating messages, such as using Transport Layer Security, while the latter can be frustrated by onion routing.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Anycast is normally highly reliable, as it can provide automatic failover without adding complexity or new potential points of failure.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Anycast applications typically feature external "heartbeat" monitoring of the server's function, and withdraw the route announcement if the server fails.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] In some cases this is done by the actual servers announcing the anycast prefix to the router over OSPF or another IGP.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] If the servers die, the router will automatically withdraw the announcement.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] "Heartbeat" functionality is important because, if the announcement continues for a failed server, the server will act as a "black hole" for nearby clients; this is the most serious mode of failure for an anycast system.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Even in this event, this kind of failure will only cause a total failure for clients that are closer to this server than any other, and will not cause a global failure.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] However, even the automation necessary to implement "heartbeat" routing withdrawal can itself add a potential point of failure, as seen in the 2021 Facebook outage.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] In denial-of-service attacks, a rogue network host may advertise itself as an anycast server for a vital network service, to provide false information or simply block service.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Anycast methodologies on the Internet may be exploited to distribute DDoS attacks and reduce their effectiveness: As traffic is routed to the closest node, a process over which the attacker has no control, the DDoS traffic flow will be distributed amongst the closest nodes.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] This may be a reason to deploy anycast addressing.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] The effectiveness of this technique depends upon maintaining the secrecy of any unicast addresses associated with anycast service nodes, however, since an attacker in possession of the unicast addresses of individual nodes can attack them from any location, bypassing anycast addressing methods.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Some anycast deployments on the Internet distinguish between local and global nodes to benefit the local community, by addressing local nodes preferentially.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Local nodes are often announced with the no-export BGP community to prevent hosts from announcing them to their peers, i.e. the announcement is kept in the local area.
[src:anycast-routing/anycast] Where both local and global nodes are deployed, the announcements from global nodes are often AS prepended (i.e. the AS is added a few more times) to make the path longer so that a local node announcement is preferred over a global node announcement.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] BGP used for routing within an autonomous system is called **Interior Border Gateway Protocol** (**iBGP**).
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In contrast, the Internet application of the protocol is called **Exterior Border Gateway Protocol** (**EBGP**).
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In January 1989, at the 12th IETF meeting in Austin, Texas, Yakov Rekhter, Len Bosack, and Kirk Lougheed sat down at a table to design what ultimately became the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP).
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The initial BGP design was recorded on two napkins, hence often referenced to as the “Two-Napkin Protocol”.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The design on the napkins was expanded to three hand-written sheets of paper from which the first interoperable BGP implementation was quickly developed.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A photocopy of these three sheets of paper now hangs on the wall of a routing protocol development area at Cisco Systems in Milpitas, California.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In the same year, RFC 1105 was published, and the BGP protocol (in various forms) has been in use on the Internet since 1994.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Half a year after the initial publication, the protocol definition was changed in 1990 with the publication of RFC 1136.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In October 1991, BGP version 3 was defined in RFC 1267, obsoleting the two earlier versions.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In 1994, the current version (BGP4), was published as RFC 1654.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Its definition was replaced in March 1995 by RFC 1771.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In January 2006, RFC 4271 was published, which currently is the latest definition of BGP4 (although updated by many other RFCs).
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] RFC 4271 corrected errors, clarified ambiguities and updated the specification with common industry practices.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The major enhancement of BGP4 was the support for Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) and use of route aggregation to decrease the size of routing tables.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In its native form, the BGP4 protocol can only work with IPv4 addresses.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Since the publication of RFC 2283 in 1998, routing information about a wide range of "address families" (IPv4, IPv6, IPX, etc.) can be carried.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The 'Multiprotocol Extensions' have been updated in 2000 with RFC 2858 and finally in 2007 with RFC 4760.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] With these extensions, the protocol is also referred to as Multiprotocol BGP (MP-BGP).
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] BGP neighbors, called peers, are established by manual configuration among routers to create a TCP session on port 179.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A BGP speaker sends 19-byte keep-alive messages every 30 seconds (protocol default value, tunable) to maintain the connection.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Among routing protocols, BGP is unique in using TCP as its transport protocol.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] When BGP runs between two peers in the same autonomous system (AS), it is referred to as *Internal BGP* (*iBGP* or *Interior Border Gateway Protocol*).
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] When it runs between different autonomous systems, it is called *External BGP* (*eBGP* or *Exterior Border Gateway Protocol*).
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Routers on the boundary of one AS exchanging information with another AS are called *border* or *edge routers* or simply *eBGP peers* and are typically connected directly, while *iBGP peers* can be interconnected through other intermediate routers.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Other deployment topologies are also possible, such as running eBGP peering inside a VPN tunnel, allowing two remote sites to exchange routing information in a secure and isolated manner.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] These route-propagation rules effectively require that all iBGP peers inside an AS are interconnected in a full mesh with iBGP sessions.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] How routes are propagated can be controlled in detail via the *route-maps* mechanism.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This mechanism consists of a set of rules.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Each rule describes, for routes matching some given criteria, what action should be taken.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The action could be to drop the route, or it could be to modify some attributes of the route before inserting it in the routing table.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] During the peering handshake, when OPEN messages are exchanged, BGP speakers can negotiate optional capabilities of the session, including multiprotocol extensions and various recovery modes.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If the multiprotocol extensions to BGP are negotiated at the time of creation, the BGP speaker can prefix the Network Layer Reachability Information (NLRI) it advertises with an address family prefix.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] These families include the IPv4 (default), IPv6, IPv4/IPv6 Virtual Private Networks and multicast BGP.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Increasingly, BGP is used as a generalized signaling protocol to carry information about routes that may not be part of the global Internet, such as VPNs.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In order to make decisions in its operations with peers, a BGP peer uses a simple finite-state machine (FSM) that consists of six states: Idle; Connect; Active; OpenSent; OpenConfirm; and Established.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] For each peer-to-peer session, a BGP implementation maintains a state variable that tracks which of these six states the session is in.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The BGP defines the messages that each peer should exchange in order to change the session from one state to another.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In the Idle state, BGP initializes all resources, refuses all inbound BGP connection attempts and initiates a TCP connection to the peer.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In the Connect state, the router waits for the TCP connection to complete and transitions to the OpenSent state if successful.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If unsuccessful, it starts the ConnectRetry timer and transitions to the Active state upon expiration.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In the Active state, the router resets the ConnectRetry timer to zero and returns to the Connect state.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In the OpenSent state, the router sends an Open message and waits for one in return in order to transition to the OpenConfirm state.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Keepalive messages are exchanged and, upon successful receipt, the router is placed into the Established state.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In the Established state, the router can send and receive: Keepalive; Update; and Notification messages to and from its peer.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In the simplest arrangement, all routers within a single AS and participating in BGP routing must be configured in a full mesh: each router must be configured as a peer to every other router.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This causes scaling problems, since the number of required connections grows quadratically with the number of routers involved.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] To alleviate the problem, BGP implements two options: route reflectors (RFC 4456) and BGP confederations (RFC 5065).
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The following discussion of basic update processing assumes a full iBGP mesh.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A given BGP router may accept network-layer reachability information (NLRI) updates from multiple neighbors and advertise NLRI to the same, or a different set, of neighbors.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The physical storage and structure of these conceptual tables are decided by the implementer of the BGP code.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Their structure is not visible to other BGP routers, although they usually can be interrogated with management commands on the local router.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] It is quite common, for example, to store the `Adj-RIB-In`, `Adj-RIB-Out` and the `Loc-RIB` together in the same data structure, with additional information attached to the RIB entries.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] BGP submits the routes that it considers best to the main routing table process.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Depending on the implementation of that process, the BGP route is not necessarily selected.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] For example, a directly connected prefix, learned from the router's own hardware, is usually most preferred.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] As long as that directly connected route's interface is active, the BGP route to the destination will not be put into the routing table.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Once the interface goes down and there are no more preferred routes, the Loc-RIB route would be installed in the main routing table.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] BGP carries the information with which rules inside BGP-speaking routers can make policy decisions.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The BGP standard specifies a number of decision factors, more than the ones that are used by any other common routing process, for selecting NLRI to go into the Loc-RIB.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The first decision point for evaluating NLRI is that its next-hop attribute must be reachable (or resolvable).
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Another way of saying the next-hop must be reachable is that there must be an active route, already in the main routing table of the router, to the prefix in which the next-hop address is reachable.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Next, for each neighbor, the BGP process applies various standard and implementation-dependent criteria to decide which routes conceptually should go into the Adj-RIB-In.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The neighbor could send several possible routes to a destination, but the first level of preference is at the neighbor level.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Only one route to each destination will be installed in the conceptual Adj-RIB-In.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This process will also delete, from the Adj-RIB-In, any routes that are withdrawn by the neighbor.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Whenever a conceptual Adj-RIB-In changes, the main BGP process decides if any of the neighbor's new routes are preferred to routes already in the Loc-RIB.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If a given route is withdrawn by a neighbor, and there is no other route to that destination, the route is removed from the Loc-RIB and no longer sent by BGP to the main routing table manager.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If the router does not have a route to that destination from any non-BGP source, the withdrawn route will be removed from the main routing table.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] As long as there is a tie, the route selection process moves to the next step.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The local preference, weight, and other criteria can be manipulated by local configuration and software capabilities.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Such manipulation, although commonly used, is outside the scope of the standard.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] For example, the *community* attribute (see below) is not directly used by the BGP selection process.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The BGP neighbor process can have a rule to set local preference or another factor based on a manually programmed rule to set the attribute if the community value matches some pattern-matching criterion.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If the route was learned from an external peer the per-neighbor BGP process computes a local preference value from local policy rules and then compares the local preference of all routes from the neighbor.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] BGP communities are attribute tags that can be applied to incoming or outgoing prefixes to achieve some common goal.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] While it is common to say that BGP allows an administrator to set policies on how prefixes are handled by ISPs, this is generally not possible, strictly speaking.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] For instance, BGP natively has no concept to allow one AS to tell another AS to restrict advertisement of a prefix to only North American peering customers.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Instead, an ISP generally publishes a list of well-known or proprietary communities with a description for each one, which essentially becomes an agreement of how prefixes are to be treated.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The customer simply adjusts their configuration to include the correct community or communities for each route, and the ISP is responsible for controlling who the prefix is advertised to.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The end user has no technical ability to enforce correct actions being taken by the ISP, though problems in this area are generally rare and accidental.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] It is a common tactic for end customers to use BGP communities (usually ASN:70,80,90,100) to control the local preference the ISP assigns to advertised routes instead of using MED (the effect is similar).
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The community attribute is transitive, but communities applied by the customer very rarely propagate outside the next-hop AS.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Not all ISPs give out their communities to the public.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The BGP Extended Community Attribute was added in 2006, in order to extend the range of such attributes and to provide a community attribute structuring by means of a type field.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The extended format consists of one or two octets for the type field, followed by seven or six octets for the respective community attribute content.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The IANA administers the registry for BGP Extended Communities Types.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The Extended Communities Attribute itself is a transitive optional BGP attribute.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A bit in the *Type* field within the attribute decides whether the encoded extended community is of a transitive or non-transitive nature.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The IANA registry therefore provides different number ranges for the attribute types.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Due to the extended attribute range, its usage can be manifold.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] RFC 4360 exemplarily defines the "Two-Octet AS Specific Extended Community", the "IPv4 Address Specific Extended Community", the "Opaque Extended Community", the "Route Target Community", and the "Route Origin Community".
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A number of BGP QoS drafts also use this Extended Community Attribute structure for inter-domain QoS signalling.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] With the introduction of 32-bit AS numbers, some issues were immediately obvious with the community attribute that only defines a 16-bit ASN field, which prevents the matching between this field and the real ASN value.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Since 2014, extended communities are compatible with 32-bit ASNs.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] To accommodate 32-bit AS numbers in BGP Communities, a Large Community attribute of 12 bytes was defined, divided in three field of 4 bytes each (AS:function:parameter).
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] MEDs, defined in the main BGP standard, were originally intended to show to another neighbor AS the advertising AS's preference as to which of several links are preferred for inbound traffic.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Another application of MEDs is to advertise the value, typically based on delay, of multiple ASs that have a presence at an IXP, that they impose to send traffic to some destination.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Some routers (like Juniper) will use the Metric from OSPF to set MED.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] All BGP messages share the following header layout.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Included for compatibility, MUST be set to all ones.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Total length of the message in octets, including the header.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] With an *Open* packet, a BGP session may be initiated.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Timeout timer, used to calculate KeepAlive messages.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Total length of the Parameters field in octets.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] field is zero, there are no parameters in the message.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This field is used to convey the capabilities the sender of this packet has to the peer.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] After the initial exchange, only differences (add/change/remove) are sent.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Length of the following withdrawn routes.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Length of the following path attributes.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Reachability information, specified as a series of <length, prefix> tuples.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If there is an error, it is because one of the fields in the OPEN or UPDATE message does not match between the peers.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] For example: BGP version mismatch, or the peering router expects a different 'My AS'.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The router then sends a Notification message to the peer indicating why the error occurred.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] An error in the communication usually leads to the teardown of the BGP session.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] To avoid a cascade of sessions being terminated due to a single error, which can happen in complex scenarios with routers with limited capabilities, extra effort is taken to isolate the problem and keep most sessions going.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A value indicating the type or origin of the error.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A value specifying which error occurred.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Optional data to help diagnose the problem.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] KeepAlive messages are sent periodically, by both peers of a session, to verify that the remote peer is still alive.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] They should be sent at intervals of one third the `holdtime`.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A keep-alive packet has no data content.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] An addition to the initial BGP message types is route-refresh, which allows for soft updating of `Adj-RIB-in`, without resetting the connection.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Before making use of this feature, the capability 'Route Refresh Capability (2)' should be specified in the 'Open' message.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Fine-grained routing updates may be acquired when the capability 'Enhanced Route Refresh Capability (70)' is also given.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This field indicates what kind of route-refresh message this is.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This field provides additional information about the type of the Network Layer Reachability Information (NLRI) carried in the attribute.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] An autonomous system with internal BGP (iBGP) must have all of its iBGP peers connect to each other in a full mesh (where everyone speaks to everyone directly).
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This full-mesh configuration requires that each router maintain a session with every other router.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In large networks, this number of sessions may degrade the performance of routers, due to either a lack of memory or high CPU process requirements.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This approach, similar to OSPF's DR/BDR feature, provides large networks with added iBGP scalability.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In a fully meshed iBGP network of 10 routers, 90 individual CLI statements (spread throughout all routers in the topology) are needed just to define the remote-AS of each peer: this quickly becomes a headache to manage.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] An RR topology can cut these 90 statements down to 18, offering a viable solution for the larger networks administered by ISPs.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] An RR is a single point of failure, therefore at least a second RR may be configured in order to provide redundancy.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] As it is an additional peer for the other 10 routers, it approximately doubles the number of CLI statements, requiring an additional 11 × 2 − 2 = 20 statements in this case.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In a BGP multipath environment, the additional RR can also benefit the network by adding local routing throughput if the RRs are acting as traditional routers instead of just a dedicated RR server role.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] RRs and confederations both reduce the number of iBGP peers to each router and thus reduce processing overhead.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] RRs are a pure performance-enhancing technique, while confederations can also be used to implement more fine-grained policy.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The *cluster ID* is then attached to every route advertised by the RR to its client or non-client peers.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A cluster ID is a cumulative, non-transitive BGP attribute, and every RR must prepend the local cluster ID to the cluster list to avoid routing loops.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Confederations are sets of autonomous systems.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In common practice, only one of the confederation AS numbers is seen by the Internet as a whole.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Confederations are used in very large networks where a large AS can be configured to encompass smaller, more manageable internal ASs.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The confederated AS is composed of multiple ASs.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Each confederated AS alone has iBGP fully meshed and has connections to other ASs inside the confederation.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Even though these ASs have eBGP peers to ASs within the confederation, the ASs exchange routing as if they used iBGP.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In this way, the confederation preserves next hop, metric, and local preference information.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] To the outside world, the confederation appears to be a single AS.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] With this solution, iBGP transit AS problems can be resolved as iBGP requires a full mesh between all BGP routers: a large number of TCP sessions and unnecessary duplication of routing traffic.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Confederations can be used in conjunction with route reflectors.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Both confederations and route reflectors can be subject to persistent oscillation unless specific design rules, affecting both BGP and the interior routing protocol, are followed.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Additionally, route reflectors and BGP confederations were not designed to ease BGP router configuration.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Nevertheless, these are common tools for experienced BGP network architects.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] These tools may be combined, for example, as a hierarchy of route reflectors.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The routing tables managed by a BGP implementation are adjusted continually to reflect actual changes in the network, such as links or routers going down and coming back up.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In the network as a whole, it is normal for these changes to happen almost continuously, but for any particular router or link, changes are expected to be relatively infrequent.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If a router is misconfigured or mismanaged, then it may get into a rapid cycle between down and up states.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This pattern of repeated withdrawal and re-announcement, known as route flapping can cause excessive activity in all the other routers that know about the cycling entity, as the same route is continually injected and withdrawn from the routing tables.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The BGP design is such that delivery of traffic may not function while routes are being updated.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] On the Internet, a BGP routing change may cause outages for several minutes.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A feature known as *route flap damping* is built into many BGP implementations, in an attempt to mitigate the effects of route flapping.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Without damping, the excessive activity can cause a heavy processing load on routers, which may in turn delay updates on other routes, and so affect overall routing stability.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] With damping, a route's flapping is exponentially decayed.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] At the first instance, when a route becomes unavailable and quickly reappears, damping does not take effect, so as to maintain the normal fail-over times of BGP.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] At the second occurrence, BGP shuns that prefix for a certain length of time; subsequent occurrences are ignored exponentially longer.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] After the abnormalities have ceased and a suitable length of time has passed for the offending route, prefixes can be reinstated with a clean slate.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Damping can also mitigate denial-of-service attacks.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] It is also suggested that route flap damping is a feature more desirable if implemented to Exterior Border Gateway Protocol Sessions (eBGP sessions or simply called exterior peers) and not on Interior Border Gateway Protocol Sessions (iBGP sessions or simply called internal peers).
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] With this approach when a route flaps inside an autonomous system, it is not propagated to the external ASs – flapping a route to an eBGP will cause a chain of flapping for the particular route throughout the backbone.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This method also successfully avoids the overhead of route flap damping for iBGP sessions.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Subsequent research has shown that flap damping can actually lengthen convergence times in some cases, and can cause interruptions in connectivity even when links are not flapping.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Moreover, as backbone links and router processors have become faster, some network architects have suggested that flap damping may not be as important as it used to be, since changes to the routing table can be handled much faster by routers.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This has led the RIPE Routing Working Group to write, "With the current implementations of BGP flap damping, the application of flap damping in ISP networks is NOT recommended. ...
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If flap damping is implemented, the ISP operating that network will cause side-effects to their customers and the Internet users of their customers' content and services ... .
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] One of the largest problems faced by BGP, and indeed the Internet infrastructure as a whole, is the growth of the Internet routing table.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If the global routing table grows to the point where some older, less capable routers cannot cope with the memory requirements or the CPU load of maintaining the table, these routers will cease to be effective gateways between the parts of the Internet they connect.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In addition, and perhaps even more importantly, larger routing tables take longer to stabilize after a major connectivity change, leaving network service unreliable, or even unavailable, in the interim.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Until late 2001, the global routing table was growing exponentially, threatening an eventual widespread breakdown of connectivity.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In an attempt to prevent this, ISPs cooperated in keeping the global routing table as small as possible by using Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) and route aggregation.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] While this slowed the growth of the routing table to a linear process for several years, with the expanded demand for multihoming by end-user networks, the growth was once again superlinear by the middle of 2004.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A Y2K-like overflow triggered in 2014 for those models that were not appropriately updated.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] While a full IPv4 BGP table as of August 2014 (512k day) was in excess of 512,000 prefixes, many older routers had a limit of 512k (512,000–524,288) routing table entries.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] On August 12, 2014, outages resulting from full tables hit eBay, LastPass and Microsoft Azure, among others.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] A number of Cisco routers commonly in use had TCAM, a form of high-speed content-addressable memory, for storing BGP advertised routes.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] On impacted routers, the TCAM was by default allocated as 512k IPv4 routes and 256k IPv6 routes.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] While the reported number of IPv6 advertised routes was only about 20k, the number of advertised IPv4 routes reached the default limit, causing a spillover effect as routers attempted to compensate for the issue by using slow software routing (as opposed to fast hardware routing via TCAM).
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The main method for dealing with this issue involves operators changing the TCAM allocation to allow more IPv4 entries by reallocating some of the TCAM reserved for IPv6 routes, which requires a reboot on most routers.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The 512k problem was predicted by a number of IT professionals.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The actual allocations, which pushed the number of routes above 512k, were the announcement of about 15,000 new routes in short order, starting at 07:48 UTC.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Almost all of these routes were to Verizon Autonomous Systems 701 and 705, created as a result of the deaggregation of larger blocks, introducing thousands of new */24* routes, and making the routing table reach 515,000 entries.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] The new routes appear to have been reaggregated within 5 minutes, but instability across the Internet apparently continued for a number of hours.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Even if Verizon had not caused the routing table to exceed 512k entries in the short spike, it would have soon happened through natural growth.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Route summarization is often used to improve aggregation of the BGP global routing table, thereby reducing the necessary table size in routers of an AS.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This all counts as AS1 announcing four routes.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] At AS1, it will either be dropped or a destination unreachable ICMP message will be sent back, depending on the configuration of AS1's routers.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] If AS2 now wants to send data to prefix *172.16.192.0/18*, it will be dropped or a destination unreachable ICMP message will be sent back at the routers of AS2 (not AS1 as before), because *172.16.192.0/18* is not in the routing table.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In 1995, the first BGP-4 specification coded AS numbers on 16 bits, for 64,510 possible public AS numbers.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In 2011, only 15,000 AS numbers were still available, and projections were envisioning a complete depletion of available AS numbers in September 2013.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] In 2007 already, the AS coding was extended from 16 to 32 bits, while retaining the 16-bit AS range (0 to 65535) and its reserved AS numbers.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This now allows up to 4 billion available AS numbers.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] An additional private AS range is also defined.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] To allow the traversal of router groups not able to manage those new ASNs, the new attribute **AS4_PATH** (optional transitive) and the special 16-bit ASN **AS_TRANS** (AS23456) is used.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Another factor contributing to the growth of the routing table is the need for load balancing of multi-homed networks.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] It is not a trivial task to balance the inbound traffic to a multi-homed network across its multiple inbound paths, due to limitations of the BGP route selection process.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] For a multi-homed network, if it announces the same network blocks across all of its BGP peers, the result may be that one or several of its inbound links become congested while the other links remain under-utilized, because external networks all picked that set of congested paths as optimal.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Like most other routing protocols, BGP does not detect congestion.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] Such cases will increase the number of routes as seen on the global BGP table.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] One method to address the routing table issue associated with load balancing is to deploy Locator/Identifier Separation Protocol (BGP/LISP) gateways within an Internet exchange point to allow ingress traffic engineering across multiple links.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This technique does not increase the number of routes seen on the global BGP table.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] By design, routers running BGP accept advertised routes from other BGP routers by default.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p01] This allows for automatic and decentralized routing of traffic across the Internet, but it also leaves the Internet potentially vulnerable to accidental or malicious disruption, known as BGP hijacking.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Multiprotocol Extensions for BGP (MBGP), sometimes referred to as Multiprotocol BGP or Multicast BGP and defined in RFC 4760, is an extension to BGP that allows different types of addresses (known as address families) to be distributed in parallel.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Whereas standard BGP supports only IPv4 unicast addresses, Multiprotocol BGP supports IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and it supports unicast and multicast variants of each.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Multiprotocol BGP allows information about the topology of IP multicast-capable routers to be exchanged separately from the topology of normal IPv4 unicast routers.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Thus, it allows a multicast routing topology different from the unicast routing topology.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Although MBGP enables the exchange of inter-domain multicast routing information, other protocols, such as the Protocol Independent Multicast family, are needed to build trees and forward multicast traffic.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Another extension to BGP is multipath routing.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] This typically requires identical MED, weight, origin, and AS-path, although some implementations provide the ability to relax the AS-path checking to only expect an equal path length rather than the actual AS numbers in the path being expected to match too.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] This can then be extended further with features like Cisco's dmzlink-bw which enables a ratio of traffic sharing based on bandwidth values configured on individual links.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] By default, BGP only supports the advertisement of a single locally selected best path to its neighbors through its Update messages.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] RFC 7911 defines the **ADD-PATH** extension, which allows a BGP speaker to advertise multiple paths for the same destination to peers.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] One application for this is when using route reflectors (RRs), because then the RR can advertise all known route paths to its clients, instead of sending only a single route it selected based on its local decision process, which is likely not the best path for all of its clients.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] BGP4 is standard for Internet routing and required of most Internet service providers (ISPs) to establish routing between one another.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Very large private IP networks use BGP internally.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] An example use case is the joining of a number of large Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) networks when OSPF by itself does not scale to the size required.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Another reason to use BGP is multihoming a network for better redundancy, either to multiple access points to a single ISP or to multiple ISPs.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Routers, especially small ones intended for small office/home office (SOHO) use, may not include BGP capability.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Other commercial routers may need a specific software executable image that supports BGP, or a license that enables it.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Devices marketed as layer-3 switches are less likely to support BGP than devices marketed as routers, but many high-end layer-3 switches can run BGP.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Products marketed as switches may have a size limitation on BGP tables that is far smaller than a full Internet table plus internal routes.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] A BGP router used only for a network with a single point of entry to the Internet may have a much smaller routing table size (and hence RAM and CPU requirements) than a multihomed network.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Even simple multihoming can have a modest routing table size.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] The actual amount of memory required in a BGP router depends on the amount of BGP information exchanged with other BGP speakers and the way in which the particular router stores BGP information.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] The router may have to keep more than one copy of a route, so it can manage different policies for route advertising and acceptance to a specific neighboring AS.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] The term *view* is often used for these different policy relationships on a running router.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] If one router implementation takes more memory per route than another implementation, this may be a legitimate design choice, trading processing speed against memory.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] A full IPv4 BGP table as of September 2025 is in excess of one million prefixes.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Large ISPs may add another 50% for internal and customer routes.
[src:anycast-routing/border-gateway-protocol-p02] Again, depending on implementation, separate tables may be kept for each view of a different peer AS.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] A **content delivery network** (**CDN**) or **content distribution network** is a geographically distributed network of proxy servers and corresponding data centers.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] CDNs provide high availability and performance ("speed") through geographical distribution relative to end users, and arose in the late 1990s to alleviate the performance bottlenecks of the Internet as it was becoming a critical medium.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Since then, CDNs have grown to serve a large portion of Internet content, including text, graphics and scripts, downloadable objects (media files, software, and documents), applications (e-commerce, portals), live streaming media, on-demand streaming media, and social media services.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] CDNs are a layer in the internet ecosystem.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Content owners such as media companies and e-commerce vendors pay CDN operators to deliver their content to their end users.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] In turn, a CDN pays Internet service providers (ISPs), carriers, and network operators for hosting its servers in their data centers.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] CDN vendors may cross over into other industries like security, DDoS protection and web application firewalls (WAF), and WAN optimization.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Content delivery service providers include Akamai Technologies, Cloudflare, Amazon CloudFront, Qwilt (Cisco), Fastly, CDN77, BunnyCDN, EdgeNext, and Google Cloud CDN.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] CDN nodes are usually deployed in multiple locations, often over multiple Internet backbones.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Benefits include reducing bandwidth costs, improving page load times, and increasing the global availability of content.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] The number of nodes and servers making up a CDN varies, depending on the architecture, some reaching thousands of nodes with tens of thousands of servers on many remote points of presence (PoPs).
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Others build a global network and have a small number of geographical PoPs.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Requests for content are typically algorithmically directed to nodes that are optimal in some way.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for performance, locations that are best for serving content to the user may be chosen.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] This may be measured by choosing locations that are the fewest hops or the shortest time to the requesting client, or the highest server performance, to optimize delivery across local networks.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for cost, locations that are the least expensive may be chosen instead.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] In an optimal scenario, these two goals tend to align, as **edge servers** that are close to the end user at the edge of the network may have an advantage in performance and cost.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Most CDN providers will provide their services over a varying, defined, set of PoPs, depending on the coverage desired, such as United States, Asia-Pacific, International or Global, etc.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] These sets of PoPs can be called "edges", "edge nodes", "edge servers", or "edge networks" as they would be the closest edge of CDN assets to the end user.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] CDN providers profit either from direct fees paid by content providers using their network, or profit from the user analytics and tracking data collected as their scripts are being loaded onto customers' websites inside their browser origin.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] As such these services are being pointed out as potential privacy intrusions for the purpose of behavioral targeting and solutions are being created to restore single-origin serving and caching of resources.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] In particular, a website using a CDN may violate the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] For example, in 2021 a German court forbade the use of a CDN on a university website, because this caused the transmission of the user's IP address to the CDN, which violated the GDPR.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] CDNs serving JavaScript have also been targeted as a way to inject malicious content into pages using them.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Subresource Integrity mechanism was created in response to ensure that the page loads a script whose content is known and constrained to a hash referenced by the website author.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] The Internet was designed according to the end-to-end principle.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] This principle keeps the core network relatively simple and moves the intelligence as much as possible to the network end-points: the hosts and clients.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] As a result, the core network is specialized, optimized, and simplified to only forward data packets.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Content Delivery Networks extend the transport network by distributing on it a variety of intelligent applications employing techniques designed to optimize content delivery.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] The resulting tightly integrated overlay uses web caching, server-load balancing, request routing, and content services.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Web caches store popular content on servers that have the greatest demand for the content requested.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] These shared network appliances reduce bandwidth requirements, reduce server load, and improve the client response times for content stored in the cache.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Web caches are populated based on requests from users (pull caching) or based on preloaded content disseminated from content servers (push caching).
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Server-load balancing uses one or more techniques including service-based (global load balancing) or hardware-based (i.e. layer 4–7 switches, also known as a web switch, content switch, or multilayer switch) to share traffic among a number of servers or web caches.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Here the switch is assigned a single virtual IP address.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Traffic arriving at the switch is then directed to one of the real web servers attached to the switch.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] This has the advantage of balancing load, increasing total capacity, improving scalability, and providing increased reliability by redistributing the load of a failed web server and providing server health checks.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] A content cluster or service node can be formed using a layer 4–7 switch to balance load across a number of servers or a number of web caches within the network.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Request routing directs client requests to the content source best able to serve the request.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] This may involve directing a client request to the service node that is closest to the client, or to the one with the most capacity.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] A variety of algorithms are used to route the request.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] These include Global Server Load Balancing, DNS-based request routing, Dynamic metafile generation, HTML rewriting, and anycasting.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Proximity—choosing the closest service node—is estimated using a variety of techniques including reactive probing, proactive probing, and connection monitoring.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] CDNs use a variety of methods of content delivery including, but not limited to, manual asset copying, active web caches, and global hardware load balancers.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Several protocol suites are designed to provide access to a wide variety of content services distributed throughout a content network.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] The Internet Content Adaptation Protocol (ICAP) was developed in the late 1990s to provide an open standard for connecting application servers.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] A more recently defined and robust solution is provided by the Open Pluggable Edge Services (OPES) protocol.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] This architecture defines OPES service applications that can reside on the OPES processor itself or be executed remotely on a Callout Server.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Edge Side Includes or ESI is a small markup language for edge-level dynamic web content assembly.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] It is fairly common for websites to have generated content.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] It could be because of changing content like catalogs or forums, or because of the personalization.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] This creates a problem for caching systems.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] To overcome this problem, a group of companies created ESI.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] In *peer-to-peer (P2P)* content-delivery networks, clients provide resources as well as use them.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] This means that, unlike client–server systems, the content-centric networks can actually perform better as more users begin to access the content (especially with protocols such as Bittorrent that require users to share).
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] This property is one of the major advantages of using P2P networks because it makes the setup and running costs very small for the original content distributor.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] To incentive peers to participate in the P2P network, web3 and blockchain technologies can be used: participating nodes receive crypto tokens in exchange of their involvement.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] If content owners are not satisfied with the options or costs of a commercial CDN service, they can create their own CDN.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] A private CDN consists of PoPs (points of presence) that are only serving content for their owner.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] These PoPs can be caching servers, reverse proxies or application delivery controllers.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] It can be as simple as two caching servers, or large enough to serve petabytes of content.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] When a private CDN is deployed within a company network, it is also referred as Entreprise CDN or **eCDN**.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Large content distribution networks may even build and set up their own private network to distribute copies of content across cache locations.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Such private networks are usually used in conjunction with public networks as a backup option in case the capacity of the private network is not enough or there is a failure which leads to capacity reduction.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Since the same content has to be distributed across many locations, a variety of multicasting techniques may be used to reduce bandwidth consumption.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Over private networks, it has also been proposed to select multicast trees according to network load conditions to more efficiently utilize available network capacity.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] The rapid growth of streaming video traffic required large capital expenditures by broadband providers in order to meet this demand and retain subscribers by delivering a sufficiently good quality of experience.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] To address this, telecommunications service providers have begun to launch their own content delivery networks as a means to lessen the demands on the network backbone and reduce infrastructure investments.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Because they own the networks over which video content is transmitted, telco CDNs have advantages over traditional CDNs.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] They own the last mile and can deliver content closer to the end-user because it can be cached deep in their networks.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] This deep caching minimizes the distance that video data travels over the general Internet and delivers it more quickly and reliably.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Telco CDNs also have a built-in cost advantage since traditional CDNs must lease bandwidth from them and build the operator's margin into their own cost model.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] In addition, by operating their own content delivery infrastructure, telco operators have better control over the utilization of their resources.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Content management operations performed by CDNs are usually applied without (or with very limited) information about the network (e.g., topology, utilization etc.) of the telco-operators with which they interact or have business relationships.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] These pose a number of challenges for the telco-operators who have a limited sphere of action in face of the impact of these operations on the utilization of their resources.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] In contrast, the deployment of telco-CDNs allows operators to implement their own content management operations, which enables them to have a better control over the utilization of their resources and, as such, provide better quality of service and experience to their end users.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] In June 2011, StreamingMedia.com reported that a group of TSPs had founded an Operator Carrier Exchange (OCX) to interconnect their networks and compete more directly against large traditional CDNs like Akamai and Limelight Networks, which have extensive PoPs worldwide.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] This way, telcos are building a Federated CDN offering, which is more interesting for a content provider willing to deliver its content to the aggregated audience of this federation.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] It is likely that in a near future, other telco CDN federations will be created.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] They will grow by enrollment of new telcos joining the federation and bringing network presence and their Internet subscriber bases to the existing ones.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] The Open Caching specification by Streaming Video Technology Alliance defines a set of APIs that allows a Content Provider to deliver its content using several CDNs in a consistent way, seeing each CDN provider the same way through these APIs.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Combining several CDN services allow Content Providers to not rely on a single CDN service, especially concerned to deal with high peak audience during live events.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] There are several ways to allocate traffic to a particular CDN among the list, either client-side CDN selection, or server-side (at the Content Provider's origin) or cloud-side (in the middle, between the content origin and the audience).
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] CDN selection criteria can be performance, availability and cost.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Traditionally, CDNs have used the IP of the client's recursive DNS resolver to geo-locate the client.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] While this is a sound approach in many situations, this leads to poor client performance if the client uses a non-local recursive DNS resolver that is far away.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] For instance, a CDN may route requests from a client in India to its edge server in Singapore, if that client uses a public DNS resolver in Singapore, causing poor performance for that client.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Indeed, a recent study showed that in many countries where public DNS resolvers are in popular use, the median distance between the clients and their recursive DNS resolvers can be as high as a thousand miles.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] In August 2011, a global consortium of leading Internet service providers led by Google announced their official implementation of the edns-client-subnet IETF Internet Draft, which is intended to accurately localize DNS resolution responses.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] The initiative involves a limited number of leading DNS service providers, such as Google Public DNS, and CDN service providers as well.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] With the edns-client-subnet EDNS0 option, CDNs can now utilize the IP address of the requesting client's subnet when resolving DNS requests.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] This approach, called end-user mapping, has been adopted by CDNs and it has been shown to drastically reduce the round-trip latencies and improve performance for clients who use public DNS or other non-local resolvers.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] However, the use of EDNS0 also has drawbacks as it decreases the effectiveness of caching resolutions at the recursive resolvers, increases the total DNS resolution traffic, and raises a privacy concern of exposing the client's subnet.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Virtualization technologies are being used to deploy virtual CDNs (vCDNs) (also known as a software-defined CDN or sd-CDN) with the goal to reduce content provider costs, and at the same time, increase elasticity and decrease service delay.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] With vCDNs, it is possible to avoid traditional CDN limitations, such as performance, reliability and availability since virtual caches are deployed dynamically (as virtual machines or containers) in physical servers distributed across the provider's geographical coverage.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] As the virtual cache placement is based on both the content type and server or end-user geographic location, the vCDNs have a significant impact on service delivery and network congestion.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] To boost performance, delivery to clients from servers can use alternate non-HTTP protocols such as WebRTC and WebSockets.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] In 2017, Addy Osmani of Google started referring to software solutions that could integrate naturally with the Responsive Web Design paradigm (with particular reference to the <picture> element) as **Image CDN**s.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] The expression referred to the ability of a web architecture to serve multiple versions of the same image through HTTP, depending on the properties of the browser requesting it, as determined by either the browser or the server-side logic.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] The purpose of Image CDNs was, in Google's vision, to serve high-quality images (or, better, images perceived as high-quality by the human eye) while preserving download speed, thus contributing to a great User experience (UX).
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Arguably, the *Image CDN* term was originally a misnomer, as neither Cloudinary nor Imgix (the examples quoted by Google in the 2017 guide by Addy Osmani) were, at the time, a CDN in the classical sense of the term.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Shortly afterwards, though, several companies offered solutions that allowed developers to serve different versions of their graphical assets according to several strategies.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] Many of these solutions were built on top of traditional CDNs, such as Akamai, CloudFront, Fastly, Edgecast and Cloudflare.
[src:anycast-routing/content-delivery-network] At the same time, other solutions that already provided an image multi-serving service joined the Image CDN definition by either offering CDN functionality natively (ImageEngine) or integrating with one of the existing CDNs (Cloudinary/Akamai, Imgix/Fastly).
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] Networks are separated from each other by specialized hosts, called gateways or routers with specialized software support optimized for routing.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] **IP forwarding** algorithms in most routing software determine a route through a shortest path algorithm.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] In routers, packets arriving at an interface are examined for source and destination addressing and queued to the appropriate outgoing interface according to their destination address and a set of rules and performance metrics.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] Rules are encoded in a routing table that contains entries for all interfaces and their connected networks.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] If no rule satisfies the requirements for a network packet, it is forwarded to a default route.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] Routing tables are maintained either manually by a network administrator, or updated dynamically by a routing protocol.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] A routing protocol specifies how routers communicate and share information about the topology of the network, and the capabilities of each routing node.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] Different protocols are often used for different topologies or different application areas.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] For example, the Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) protocol is generally used within an enterprise and the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) is used on a global scale.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] BGP is the de facto standard for worldwide Internet routing.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] Routing protocols may be broadly distinguished by their realm of operation in terms of network scope.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] Interior gateway protocols are used for routing within autonomous systems, while exterior gateway protocols route traffic between them.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] The former group is exemplified by the Routing Information Protocol (RIP) and Open Shortest Path First (OSPF), while the Exterior Gateway Protocol (EGP) and the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) are examples of the exterior type.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] BGP is the dominant route distribution protocol used on the Internet.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] The IP forwarding algorithm is a specific implementation of routing for IP networks.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] In order to achieve a successful transfer of data, the algorithm uses a routing table to select a next-hop router as the next destination for a datagram.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] When multiple route table entries match, the entry with the longest subnet mask is chosen as it is the most specific one.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] If there are multiple routes with the same subnet mask, the route with the lowest metric is used.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] If there are multiple default routes, the metric is also used to determine which to use.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] If there are multiple routes with the same subnet mask and metric, the system may use equal-cost multi-path routing as a forwarding strategy.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] When no route is available, an ICMP error message is sent to the originator of the packet, to inform that host that the packet could not be delivered.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] To avoid unnecessary retransmission to avoid network congestion, the sending host should either stop transmitting or choose another address or route.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] The host has several network interfaces.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] *eth0* is the interface name of the network interface card representing an Ethernet port.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] *ppp0* is a PPPoE interface, which is configured as the default route in this example.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] A default route is recognized by the destination *0.0.0.0* and the flag *G*.
[src:anycast-routing/ip-routing] A network router is identified by the network mask *255.255.255.255* and the flag *H*.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] In its simplest implementation, round-robin DNS works by responding to DNS requests not only with a single potential IP address, but with a list of potential IP addresses corresponding to several servers that host identical services.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] The order in which IP addresses from the list are returned is the basis for the term *round robin*.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] With each DNS response, the IP address sequence in the list is permuted.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] Traditionally, IP clients initially attempt connections with the first address returned from a DNS query, so that on different connection attempts, clients would receive service from different providers, thus distributing the overall load among servers.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] Some resolvers attempt to re-order the list to give priority to numerically "closer" networks.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] This behaviour was standardized in RFC 3484 during the definition of IPv6.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] When applied to IPv4, a bug in Windows Vista caused issues and defeated round-robin load-balancing.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] Some desktop clients do try alternate addresses after a connection timeout of up to 30 seconds.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] Round-robin DNS is often used to load balance requests among a number of web servers.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] For example, a company has one domain name and three identical copies of the same web site residing on three servers with three IP addresses.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] The DNS server will be set up so that domain name has multiple A records, one for each IP address.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] When one user accesses the home page it will be sent to the first IP address.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] The second user who accesses the home page will be sent to the next IP address, and the third user will be sent to the third IP address.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] In each case, once the IP address is given out, it goes to the end of the list.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] The fourth user, therefore, will be sent to the first IP address, and so forth.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] A round-robin DNS name is, on rare occasions, referred to as a "rotor" due to the rotation among alternative A records.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] Although easy to implement, round-robin DNS has a number of drawbacks, such as those arising from record caching in the DNS hierarchy itself, as well as client-side address caching and reuse, the combination of which can be difficult to manage.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] Round-robin DNS should not solely be relied upon for service availability.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] If a service at one of the addresses in the list fails, the DNS will continue to hand out that address and clients will still attempt to reach the inoperable service.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] Round-robin DNS may not be the best choice for load balancing on its own, since it merely alternates the order of the address records each time a name server is queried.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] Because it does not take transaction time, server load, and network congestion into consideration, it works best for services with a large number of uniformly distributed connections to servers of equivalent capacity.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] Otherwise, it just does load distribution.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] Methods exist to overcome such limitations.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] For example, modified DNS servers (such as lbnamed) can routinely poll mirrored servers for availability and load factor.
[src:anycast-routing/round-robin-dns] If a server does not reply as required, the server can be temporarily removed from the DNS pool, until it reports that it is once again operating within specs.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] In computer networking, a **routing table**, or **routing information base** (**RIB**), is a data table stored in a router or a network host that lists the routes to particular network destinations, and in some cases, metrics (distances) associated with those routes.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] The routing table contains information about the topology of the network immediately around it.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] The construction of routing tables is the primary goal of routing protocols.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] Static routes are entries that are fixed, rather than resulting from routing protocols and network topology discovery procedures.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] A routing table is analogous to a distribution map in package delivery.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] Whenever a node needs to send data to another node on a network, it must first know *where* to send it.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] If the node cannot directly connect to the destination node, it has to send it via other nodes along a route to the destination node.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] Each node needs to keep track of which way to deliver various packages of data, and for this, it uses a routing table.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] A routing table is a database that keeps track of paths, like a map, and uses these to determine which way to forward traffic.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] A routing table is a data file in RAM that is used to store route information about directly connected and remote networks.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] Nodes can also share the contents of their routing table with other nodes.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] The primary function of a router is to forward a packet toward its destination network, which is the destination IP address of the packet.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] To do this, a router needs to search the routing information stored in its routing table.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] The routing table contains network/next hop associations.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] These associations tell a router that a particular destination can be optimally reached by sending the packet to a specific router that represents the next hop on the way to the final destination.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] The next hop association can also be the outgoing or exit interface to the final destination.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] With hop-by-hop routing, each routing table lists, for all reachable destinations, the address of the next device along the path to that destination: the next hop.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] Assuming that the routing tables are consistent, the simple algorithm of relaying packets to their destination's next hop thus suffices to deliver data anywhere in a network.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] Hop-by-hop is the fundamental characteristic of the IP Internet layer and the OSI Network Layer.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] When a router interface is configured with an IP address and subnet mask, the interface becomes a host on that attached network.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] A directly connected network is a network that is directly attached to one of the router interfaces.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] The network address and subnet mask of the interface, along with the interface type and number, are entered into the routing table as a directly connected network.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] A remote network is a network that can only be reached by sending the packet to another router.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] Routing table entries to remote networks may be either dynamic or static.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] Dynamic routes are routes to remote networks that were learned automatically by the router through a dynamic routing protocol.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] Static routes are routes that a network administrator manually configured.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] Routing tables are also a key aspect of certain security operations, such as unicast reverse path forwarding (uRPF).
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] In this technique, which has several variants, the router also looks up, in the routing table, the *source address* of the packet.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] If there exists no route back to the source address, the packet is assumed to be malformed or involved in a network attack and is dropped.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] The need to record routes to large numbers of devices using limited storage space represents a major challenge in routing table construction.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] On the Internet, the currently dominant address aggregation technology is a bitwise prefix matching scheme called Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR).
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] Supernetworks can also be used to help control routing table size.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] *metric*: The routing metric of the path through which the packet is to be sent.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] The route will go in the direction of the gateway with the lowest metric.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] *interface*: Such as eth0 for the first Ethernet card, eth1 for the second Ethernet card, etc.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] Routing tables are generally not used directly for packet forwarding in modern router architectures; instead, they are used to generate the information for a simpler forwarding table.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] This forwarding table contains only the routes that are chosen by the routing algorithm as preferred routes for packet forwarding.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] It is often in a compressed or pre-compiled format that is optimized for hardware storage and lookup.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] This router architecture separates the control plane function of the routing table from the forwarding plane function of the forwarding table.
[src:anycast-routing/routing-table] This separation of control and forwarding provides uninterrupted high-performance forwarding.
